{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641824","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641824"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:32:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:32:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17909"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17909","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17909"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.94,0.03,0,0.03,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10623"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78252"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10623","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10623"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17909"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63661"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10770"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24752"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24756"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26840"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78252","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78252"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EType 2 diabetes and its associations is one of the major health challenges in Australia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about type 2 diabetes is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["It is characterised by sustained hyperglycaemia and insulin resistance","It most typically affects adolescents","It is always insulin-dependent","It is characterised by hypoinsulinaemia and hypolipidaemia","It is diabetes is caused solely by genetic factors"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIt is estimated that some 1 in 20 Australians have diabetes and the majority (86%) have type 2 diabetes. Unfortunately the prevalence of diabetes continues to rise and this is a reflection on increasing obesity, the ageing population, dietary changes and sedentary lifestyles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType 2 diabetes is characterised by sustained hyperglycaemia and insulin resistance\u003C/strong\u003E. This condition results from a combination of insulin resistance and beta cell dysfunction, leading to elevated blood glucose levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType 2 diabetes most typically affects adolescents\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While it can occur in adolescents, it is more commonly diagnosed in adults, particularly those over the age of 45.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType 2 diabetes is always insulin-dependent\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Many patients with type 2 diabetes can manage their condition with lifestyle changes and oral medications, especially in the early stages. Insulin therapy may be required as the disease progresses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType 2 diabetes is characterised by hypoinsulinaemia and hypolipidaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Type 2 diabetes is associated with insulin resistance, not hypoinsulinaemia, and often with dyslipidaemia, not hypolipidaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType 2 diabetes is caused solely by genetic factors\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While genetics play a role, environmental factors such as diet, physical activity, and obesity are significant contributors to the development of type 2 diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Type 2 diabetes is characterised by insulin resistance and beta cell dysfunction.","Type 2 diabetes typically affects adults, but can also occur in adolescents.","Type 2 diabetes is not always insulin-dependent, especially in the early stages."],"references":["Banday MZ, Sameer AS, Nissar S. Pathophysiology of diabetes: An overview. Avicenna J Med. 2020 Oct 13;10(4):174-188. doi: 10.4103/ajm.ajm_53_20. PMID: 33437689; PMCID: PMC7791288.","Galicia-Garcia U, Benito-Vicente A, Jebari S, Larrea-Sebal A, Siddiqi H, Uribe KB, Ostolaza H, Mart\u00edn C. Pathophysiology of Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus. Int J Mol Sci. 2020 Aug 30;21(17):6275. doi: 10.3390/ijms21176275. PMID: 32872570; PMCID: PMC7503727.","Banday MZ, Sameer AS, Nissar S. Pathophysiology of diabetes: An overview. Avicenna J Med. 2020 Oct 13;10(4):174-188. doi: 10.4103/ajm.ajm_53_20. PMID: 33437689; PMCID: PMC7791288."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63661"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17909"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63661","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63661"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-10T09:07:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-10T09:07:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10623"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78252"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id"